## ­¤¤ó VARIABLES & SCOPE

### 4. Scope Rules
- [ ] Global scope
- [ ] Function scope
- [ ] Block scope
- [ ] Module scope (ES6)
- [ ] Lexical scope
- [ ] Scope chain
- [ ] `this` binding in different contexts
- [ ] Explicit binding: `call()`, `apply()`, `bind()`

**Key Concept**:
```javascript
// Scope chain
let global = 'global';

function outer() {
  let outerVar = 'outer';
  
  function inner() {
    let innerVar = 'inner';
    console.log(innerVar);  // inner
    console.log(outerVar);  // outer (found in parent scope)
    console.log(global);    // global (found in global scope)
  }
  
  inner();
}

// this binding
const obj = {
  name: 'John',
  greet: function() {
    console.log(this.name); // 'John' (this = obj)
  }
};

const greet = obj.greet;
greet(); // undefined (this = window/global)

// Explicit binding
greet.call(obj);        // 'John'
greet.apply(obj);       // 'John'
const boundGreet = greet.bind(obj);
boundGreet();           // 'John'
```

**Master When**: You understand scope chain and can predict `this` value correctly

---

### 5. Closures
- [ ] Definition and creation
- [ ] Lexical environment
- [ ] Memory implications
- [ ] Practical use cases
- [ ] Common closure pitfalls
- [ ] Closure patterns (factory, module)

**Key Concept**:
```javascript
// Closure - inner function accessing outer variables
function createCounter() {
  let count = 0;  // Private variable
  
  return {
    increment() {
      return ++count;
    },
    decrement() {
      return --count;
    },
    getCount() {
      return count;
    }
  };
}

const counter = createCounter();
console.log(counter.increment()); // 1
console.log(counter.increment()); // 2
console.log(counter.decrement()); // 1
console.log(counter.getCount());  // 1
// count is inaccessible from outside

// Closure pitfall - loop with var
for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100); // 3, 3, 3
}

// Fix with let
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100); // 0, 1, 2
}

// Or with closure
for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  (function(j) {
    setTimeout(() => console.log(j), 100); // 0, 1, 2
  })(i);
}
```

**Master When**: You can identify closure patterns and explain memory implications

