## ­¤ö┤ OBJECTS & PROTOTYPES

### 11. Prototypal Inheritance
- [ ] Prototype property and chain
- [ ] `Object.create()`
- [ ] `Object.getPrototypeOf()` and `Object.setPrototypeOf()`
- [ ] Prototype methods vs instance methods
- [ ] Property lookup in prototype chain
- [ ] Shadowing properties

**Key Concept**:
```javascript
// Prototype chain
const animal = {
  speak() { console.log('Sound'); }
};

const dog = Object.create(animal);
dog.name = 'Rex';

dog.speak(); // 'Sound' (found in prototype)
console.log(dog.hasOwnProperty('speak')); // false
console.log('speak' in dog); // true

// Prototype property
function Animal(name) {
  this.name = name;
}

Animal.prototype.speak = function() {
  console.log(`${this.name} makes a sound`);
};

const cat = new Animal('Whiskers');
cat.speak(); // 'Whiskers makes a sound'

// Property lookup
console.log(cat.name);        // 'Whiskers' (own property)
console.log(cat.speak);       // function (found in prototype)
console.log(cat.hasOwnProperty('speak')); // false
```

**Master When**: You understand the prototype chain and can explain property lookup

---

### 12. Constructor Functions & new Operator
- [ ] Constructor function pattern
- [ ] `new` operator behavior
- [ ] Constructor.prototype
- [ ] Instance vs prototype properties
- [ ] Returning from constructor
- [ ] Constructor pattern vs factory pattern

**Key Concept**:
```javascript
// Constructor function
function Person(name, age) {
  this.name = name;
  this.age = age;
}

Person.prototype.greet = function() {
  return `Hi, I'm ${this.name}`;
};

const john = new Person('John', 30);
console.log(john.greet()); // "Hi, I'm John"

// What 'new' does:
// 1. Create empty object: {}
// 2. Set [[Prototype]]: obj.__proto__ = Person.prototype
// 3. Call function with this = obj
// 4. Return object if not already returned

// Constructor vs Factory
// Constructor (uses 'new')
function Dog(name) {
  this.name = name;
}
const d1 = new Dog('Rex');

// Factory (no 'new')
function createDog(name) {
  return { name };
}
const d2 = createDog('Rex');
```

**Master When**: You understand what `new` does and can choose constructor vs factory patterns

---

### 13. ES6 Classes
- [ ] Class syntax
- [ ] Constructor method
- [ ] Instance methods
- [ ] Static methods
- [ ] Getters and setters
- [ ] Private fields (with `#`)
- [ ] Inheritance with `extends` and `super`
- [ ] Class expressions

**Key Concept**:
```javascript
// Basic class
class Animal {
  constructor(name) {
    this.name = name;
  }
  
  speak() {
    console.log(`${this.name} makes a sound`);
  }
  
  static info() {
    return 'I am an Animal class';
  }
}

const dog = new Animal('Rex');
dog.speak(); // 'Rex makes a sound'
Animal.info(); // 'I am an Animal class'

// Inheritance
class Dog extends Animal {
  constructor(name, breed) {
    super(name);
    this.breed = breed;
  }
  
  speak() {
    console.log(`${this.name} barks`);
  }
}

const myDog = new Dog('Buddy', 'Golden');
myDog.speak(); // 'Buddy barks'

// Private fields
class Secret {
  #privateField = 'hidden';
  
  getPrivate() {
    return this.#privateField;
  }
}

const s = new Secret();
console.log(s.getPrivate()); // 'hidden'
console.log(s.#privateField); // SyntaxError
```

**Master When**: You can use classes effectively and understand they're syntax sugar over prototypes

