## ­¤ö┤ ASYNCHRONOUS PROGRAMMING

### 14. Callbacks
- [ ] Callback functions
- [ ] Callback hell/pyramid of doom
- [ ] Callback patterns
- [ ] Error-first callbacks (Node.js style)
- [ ] setTimeout and setInterval
- [ ] RequestAnimationFrame (RAF)

**Key Concept**:
```javascript
// Basic callback
function fetchData(callback) {
  setTimeout(() => {
    callback('Data received');
  }, 1000);
}

fetchData((data) => {
  console.log(data); // 'Data received'
});

// Error-first callback
function readFile(path, callback) {
  setTimeout(() => {
    const error = path === '' ? new Error('Invalid path') : null;
    const data = error ? null : 'File content';
    callback(error, data);
  }, 100);
}

readFile('/file.txt', (err, data) => {
  if (err) console.error(err);
  else console.log(data);
});

// Callback hell
fetchUser(userId, (user) => {
  fetchPosts(user.id, (posts) => {
    fetchComments(posts[0].id, (comments) => {
      console.log(comments);
    });
  });
});

// Solution: Promises or Async/Await
```

**Master When**: You understand callback limitations and why Promises are better

---

### 15. Promises
- [ ] Promise states: pending, fulfilled, rejected
- [ ] Creating promises with `new Promise()`
- [ ] `then()`, `catch()`, `finally()`
- [ ] Promise chaining
- [ ] `Promise.all()`, `Promise.race()`, `Promise.allSettled()`, `Promise.any()`
- [ ] Promise error handling
- [ ] Promise static methods

**Key Concept**:
```javascript
// Creating a promise
const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  setTimeout(() => {
    if (Math.random() > 0.5) {
      resolve('Success!');
    } else {
      reject(new Error('Failed!'));
    }
  }, 1000);
});

// Consuming a promise
promise
  .then((result) => console.log(result))
  .catch((error) => console.error(error))
  .finally(() => console.log('Done'));

// Promise chaining
fetch('/api/user')
  .then((response) => response.json())
  .then((user) => fetch(`/api/posts/${user.id}`))
  .then((response) => response.json())
  .then((posts) => console.log(posts))
  .catch((error) => console.error(error));

// Promise utilities
Promise.all([p1, p2, p3])         // All must succeed
  .then((results) => console.log(results));

Promise.race([p1, p2, p3])        // First to settle
  .then((result) => console.log(result));

Promise.allSettled([p1, p2, p3])  // All settle (any state)
  .then((results) => console.log(results));

Promise.any([p1, p2, p3])         // First success
  .then((result) => console.log(result));
```

**Master When**: You understand all Promise methods and can handle errors properly

---

### 16. Async/Await
- [ ] Async functions always return promises
- [ ] Await operator
- [ ] Error handling with try/catch
- [ ] Parallel vs sequential execution
- [ ] Async loops and iterations
- [ ] Async function return values
- [ ] Common pitfalls

**Key Concept**:
```javascript
// Basic async/await
async function fetchUser(id) {
  try {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/user/${id}`);
    const user = await response.json();
    return user;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Failed to fetch user:', error);
  }
}

fetchUser(1).then((user) => console.log(user));

// Sequential vs Parallel
// Sequential (slower)
async function sequential() {
  const user = await fetchUser(1);      // Wait 1s
  const posts = await fetchPosts(user.id); // Wait 1s
  return { user, posts };              // Total: 2s
}

// Parallel (faster)
async function parallel() {
  const [user, posts] = await Promise.all([
    fetchUser(1),              // Start now
    fetchPosts(1)              // Start now
  ]);                          // Total: 1s
  return { user, posts };
}

// Async loops
async function fetchAll(ids) {
  // Sequential
  for (const id of ids) {
    const user = await fetchUser(id);
    console.log(user);
  }
  
  // Parallel
  const users = await Promise.all(ids.map(id => fetchUser(id)));
  return users;
}

// Common pitfall - forgetting await
async function bad() {
  const data = fetchData(); // Returns promise, not data
  console.log(data); // Promise object, not data
}

async function good() {
  const data = await fetchData(); // Wait for result
  console.log(data); // Actual data
}
```

**Master When**: You choose sequential vs parallel execution appropriately

