## ­¤¤Ī FUNCTIONAL PROGRAMMING

### 28. Pure Functions & Immutability
- [ ] Pure functions definition
- [ ] Side effects
- [ ] Immutability in JavaScript
- [ ] Const doesn't mean immutable
- [ ] Immutable data structures
- [ ] Object.freeze() and Object.seal()

**Key Concept**:
```javascript
// Pure function - same input = same output, no side effects
const add = (a, b) => a + b;  // Pure
const multiply = (a, b) => a * b;  // Pure

// Impure - side effects
let total = 0;
const addToTotal = (x) => {
  total += x;  // Modifies external state
  return total;
};

// Immutability
const original = { name: 'John', age: 30 };
const updated = { ...original, age: 31 }; // Creates new object
console.log(original.age); // 30 (unchanged)

// Immutable array operations
const arr = [1, 2, 3];
const newArr = [...arr, 4]; // Doesn't mutate original
arr.push(4);                 // Mutates original

// Shallow freeze
const frozen = Object.freeze({ user: { name: 'John' } });
frozen.user = {};            // Error
frozen.user.name = 'Jane';   // Works! (shallow)

// Deep freeze
function deepFreeze(obj) {
  Object.freeze(obj);
  Object.getOwnPropertyNames(obj).forEach((name) => {
    if (typeof obj[name] === 'object') {
      deepFreeze(obj[name]);
    }
  });
  return obj;
}
```

**Master When**: You write pure functions and immutable code naturally

---

### 29. Functional Composition
- [ ] Function composition
- [ ] Compose and pipe functions
- [ ] Partial application
- [ ] Currying
- [ ] Method chaining

**Key Concept**:
```javascript
// Function composition - apply functions left to right
const compose = (...fns) => (x) => fns.reduceRight((v, fn) => fn(v), x);
const pipe = (...fns) => (x) => fns.reduce((v, fn) => fn(v), x);

const add5 = (x) => x + 5;
const multiply2 = (x) => x * 2;
const square = (x) => x * x;

// compose applies right to left: square(multiply2(add5(x)))
const composed = compose(square, multiply2, add5);
console.log(composed(3)); // ((3 + 5) * 2)^2 = 256

// pipe applies left to right: add5(multiply2(square(x)))
const piped = pipe(square, multiply2, add5);
console.log(piped(3)); // (3^2) * 2 + 5 = 23

// Currying
const curry = (fn) => {
  const arity = fn.length;
  
  return function curried(...args) {
    if (args.length >= arity) {
      return fn(...args);
    } else {
      return (...moreArgs) => curried(...args, ...moreArgs);
    }
  };
};

const add = (a, b, c) => a + b + c;
const curriedAdd = curry(add);
console.log(curriedAdd(1)(2)(3)); // 6
console.log(curriedAdd(1, 2)(3)); // 6
```

**Master When**: You compose functions elegantly

