## ­¤ö┤ SECURITY

### 32. Security Best Practices
- [ ] XSS (Cross-Site Scripting) prevention
- [ ] CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery)
- [ ] SQL Injection
- [ ] Input validation and sanitization
- [ ] Content Security Policy (CSP)
- [ ] Secure headers
- [ ] CORS

**Key Concept**:
```javascript
// XSS Prevention - Don't use innerHTML with untrusted data
// BAD
element.innerHTML = userInput; // If userInput contains <script>, it executes

// GOOD
element.textContent = userInput; // Always safe
element.innerText = userInput;   // Always safe

// Or use proper escaping
function escapeHtml(text) {
  const map = {
    '&': '&amp;',
    '<': '&lt;',
    '>': '&gt;',
    '"': '&quot;',
    "'": '&#039;'
  };
  return text.replace(/[&<>"']/g, (m) => map[m]);
}

// Input validation
function validateEmail(email) {
  const regex = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/;
  return regex.test(email);
}

// CSRF Protection - use tokens
// In HTML form:
// <input type="hidden" name="csrf_token" value="unique_token">

// Then verify on backend
if (request.body.csrf_token !== session.csrf_token) {
  throw new Error('CSRF token mismatch');
}
```

**Master When**: You write secure JavaScript and validate user input

